class Solution {
    public long maximumSubarraySum(int[] nums, int k) {
        long ans = Long.MIN_VALUE;
        long sum = 0;
        Map<Integer, Long> minS = new HashMap<>();
        for (int x : nums) {
            long s1 = minS.getOrDefault(x - k, Long.MAX_VALUE / 2);
            long s2 = minS.getOrDefault(x + k, Long.MAX_VALUE / 2);
            ans = Math.max(ans, sum + x - Math.min(s1, s2));
            minS.merge(x, sum, Math::min);
            sum += x;
        }
        return ans > Long.MIN_VALUE / 4 ? ans : 0;
    }
}
```

The code first declares a long variable ans to hold the maximum sum of a good subarray, and a long variable sum to hold the sum of the elements in nums up to the current index. A HashMap minS is used to store the minimum sum of all subarrays with the last element as key.

For each element x in nums, it calculates the minimum sum of the subarray with the last element x - k and x + k. The maximum sum of a good subarray is then calculated as the maximum of ans and sum + x - the minimum of s1 and s2. The minimum sum of a subarray with the last element x is then updated in the HashMap. The sum of all elements in nums up to the current index is also updated.

Finally, if ans is greater than a certain threshold, it is returned. Otherwise, 0 is returned.

