The mask variable should be set as 1 << n. This is because 1 << n will give us a binary number that is a string of '1's with length n. 

Explanation:
The binary number 1 << n will be a string of '1's with length n. So, masking it with the integer i gives us a string of length n+1 starting with '1' and followed by all bits of i.
Then, (x >> 1) & x will check if there are any two consecutive '1's in the string. If there are, then the result of this operation will be non-zero. Therefore, ((x >> 1) & x) == 0 will be true if and only if there are no two consecutive '1's in the string.
Finally, the string will be added to the list if it doesn't contain any two consecutive '1's.

