This solution uses depth-first search (DFS) to traverse the DAG and check which team can reach all other teams. A team can only be the champion if it can reach all other teams. If there are multiple teams that can reach all other teams, it means there is no unique champion.

First, we create a graph from the edges. Each edge in the graph represents a directed edge from a team to a stronger team.

Then, for each team, we start a DFS from that team. During the DFS, we mark all teams that can be reached. If all teams can be reached, then the current team can be the champion.

If we find a team that can reach all other teams, we update the champion. If we find another team that can reach all other teams, it means there is no unique champion, so we return -1.

Finally, we return the champion. If no champion is found, we return -1.

Time complexity is O(n*(n+m)) because we potentially perform a DFS for each team, and each DFS traverses all edges. Space complexity is O(n+m) because we store the graph in an adjacency list and the visited array.

